Then, well screen the patients based on their ICD9 codes to identify those with sepsis based on a post in Stack Overflow. The codes for sepsis, severe sepsis, and septic shock are 99591, 99592, and 78552 respectively.

# Search for septic patients
search_patterns = paste(c(99591, 99592, 78552), collapse="|")

for (i in 1:nrow(cohort_data)){
  cohort_data$septic[i] <- grepl(search_patterns, cohort_data[i, 'icd9_code'])
}

kable(head(cohort_data), caption="Sample of cohort data from Part 1 after searching for sepsis diagnosis.") %>%

To visualize the relative proportion of patients in the cohort who were septic, I create a pie chart using the graphics package ggplot2. While pie-charts are often not ideal, since we only have two categories (septic or not), this is an acceptable use case.

# Plot pie chart
fig <- ggplot(cohort_data, aes(x=factor(1), fill=septic)) +
  geom_bar(width=1) +
  coord_polar('y') +
  xlab('') + ylab('') + ggtitle(sprintf('Pie Chart of Septic vs. Non-septic Patients')) +
  scale_fill_discrete(name='Diagnosed sepsis') +
  theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(), axis.title.y=element_blank(),
        axis.text.x=element_blank(), axis.text.y=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x=element_blank(), axis.ticks.y=element_blank(),
        panel.background=element_blank(), panel.border=element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major=element_blank(), panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
        plot.background=element_blank())

print(fig)

We can see that in our sample of 5000 patients, 495 out of 5000 patients (9.90%) were diagnosed with sepsis, severe sepsis, or septic shock.

1.1 Remove missing variables

Well also choose to remove rows that contain missing variables - this makes visualization and exploratory data analysis easier, while unfortunately reducing our overall sample size.

cohort_data = cohort_data[complete.cases(cohort_data),]

After removing rows with missing values, were left with 3119 subjects. This is still plenty for our analysis. In our new dataset, 13.85% of patients were diagnosed with sepsis. This event rate is slightly higher than the before removing missing values - we can theorize that septic patients are likely being monitored especially for SIRS criteria, and thus are more likely to receive the full compliment of tests.

2 Exploring individual variables

Next, we can explore the individual variables collected as part of the SIRS scoring system. First, Ill create a plotHistogram() function, which then can be called for each variable. Ill also create a compareDistribution() function to plot the kernel density estimate (KDE) by group.

# Plot histogram, given the dataframe, the x-data, and the title.
plotHistogram <- function(d, xdata, title){
  fig <- ggplot(data=d, aes(x=d[,xdata])) +
    geom_histogram() + 
    ggtitle(sprintf('Histogram of %s', title)) + xlab(title)
}

# Plot density plots of temperature, given the dataframe, the x-data, grouping variable, and the title.
compareDistribution <- function(d, xdata, grouping_var, title){
  fig <- ggplot(data=d, aes(x=d[,xdata], fill=d[,grouping_var])) +
    geom_density(alpha=0.5) + 
    scale_fill_discrete(name='Diagnosed sepsis') +
    ylab('Kernel Density Estimate') + 
    ggtitle(sprintf('Grouped KDE of %s', title)) + xlab(title)
}

2.2 Temperature

The first variable on our list is temperature. Well plot the histogram of the overall temperature and the the kernel density estimation of the two groups next to it.

ggarrange(
  plotHistogram(cohort_data, 'temperature', 'Temperature (C)'),
  compareDistribution(cohort_data, 'temperature', 'septic', 'Temperature (C)'),
  ncol=2
)
